Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A lunatic asylum, where young people meet today.
A chapel in a tomb, where the subway tunnel is being dug.
Smallholders are farming the former farmland of peasants.
The oldest official map of Munich brings exciting stories to life.
It's annoying when maps aren't up to date.
Anyone who has ever had to get upset because the car navigation system indicated a green meadow instead of a bypass road knows this.
The historical maps of the Bavarian Digital Atlas, a service of the Bavarian State Government Geoportal, are far from up-to-date - but very informative for that very reason.
Especially when you compare them to current online maps.
The study will show how cities and towns in the Munich Mercury's distribution area have changed since the 19th century.
The Bavarian Digital Atlas is a patchwork of texts that is not immediately recognized as such.
The large overview map has been supplemented by more detailed maps for towns and municipalities, called urposition sheets.
These were created according to the Bavarian Survey Administration between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
It was commissioned by Napoleon.
The French general occupied Bavaria from the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographic survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Although the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the present-day neighbors who created the idea of a comprehensive Bavarian map.
Elector Max IV. Joseph took the project further, founding the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original copy for Munich dates from 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bavarian State Library.
The comparison between the past and the present is most striking in the case of the provincial capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example is the Unterendling, which appears relatively isolated in the 1856 map.
Sendling was incorporated as a borough of Munich 21 years after the map was created, in 1877.
Today, the underbelly is in the middle of the city.
The houses of the Unterendlings are concentrated around 1856 along today's Plinganserstraße, which was named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser in 1878, a leader of the uprising of the Bavarian peasants against Austria in 1705.
Where Westpark is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance: a map with dozens of lines and numbers appears in smaller detail: hand-numbered parcels of land from the so-called "collection" from which the land tax was derived.
Small plots are no longer occupied by farmers - but by small gardeners from the "Land in Sun" plant.
A large green area is visible north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, which has been the scene of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was actually a meadow in the 19th century - not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives a glimpse into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the area of the present district of Au-Haidhausen, the original tax form not only shows the street name "am Gasteig" or the hill "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here at Auerfeldstraße they used to lock up people with delusions.
There, in 1858/59, the Munich district insane asylum "Auf der Auer Lüften" was created.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden, the psychiatrist associated with the death of King Louis II, ran the institution.
"He was ahead of his time, and ended, for example, the chain of the so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff to use violence against the inmates", says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, which has been working with the institution for an exhibition.
Initially, the hospital had a capacity of 280 patients, but this was later increased to 500 patients.
At some point this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district hospital in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum Munich-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
The former Auer Institute is now the meeting place for young people in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities.
To the west is the TSV München Ost football field, to the east are residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's home "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in architectural style of the original building of the insane asylum, which had been destroyed in bombing raids during World War II.
The Marienplatz was recorded around 1856 as "Main Platz", the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought about a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs in December 1944 tore many holes in the city center.
A large one remains today - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a medieval chapel were once located at the Marienhof, where the preliminary work and the groundbreaking for the second S-Bahn main line take place on 5 April 2017.
The sliding control allows the old Munich map to be compared with the aerial view of today - and fill the hole at Marienhof.
Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color who travel to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racial attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is set to take effect by August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable race-based incidents have occurred recently throughout the state and are noted here", the group's statement said.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"You have civil rights violations that people are going through.
They are stopped because of the color of their skin, they are beaten or killed", Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We are hearing complaints at a frequency we have never heard before".
It is the first such warning the organization has issued to a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist abuse against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas on a statewide trip and being taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The Council also points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's office showing that black motorists are 75 percent more likely to be stopped in the state than white drivers.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People have to be willing to bring bail money or let relatives know they're traveling across state".
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest numbers from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, which ranks the state 16th in the nation in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also in response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws that obligated local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are typically issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
