The total area of the open space is 35 hectares, and the estimated cost is more than EUR 112 000.
Is there nothing sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The most obvious sign of a regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
Americans value this as much as any other - hence the carefully staged overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdous Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic ax to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller didn't attack the statue himself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty imitators would have lynched him if he'd done it.
But he attacked its meaning, and in particular the meaning that was ascribed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller chided Acosta, "I don't want to get into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you refer to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller is factually correct, but as he himself put it, it's not really about history.
It is about the contemporary response to the shocking words of Lazarus, the only one in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your weary, your poor, / your oppressed masses who yearn to breathe freely, / the wretched waste of your rich shores".
There has never been a time when the "miserable waste" has been more visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literary criticism - he was making it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's America.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural dispute: it is, in fact, a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus and her friends, who were committed to putting her words on the base after her death, knew very well that they were committing a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the links between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in an outdated classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has been given a voice.
And she gives herself a very different name: Mother of the Exilets.
The combination of the poem and the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, right-wingers have long wanted to change it back.
The great scribe Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative bringing the American flame into the night-time world: "Lady Liberty goes on ahead.
It's supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way to the United States".
Quite unusual, Limbaugh has stumbled upon something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of perception.
Lazarus's great act of fantasy was to see her as she was seen by the tired, wretched, but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
It's about, in the truest sense, seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to better their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that's not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to ignite hatred, which is their only source of power.
