Blocking critics via Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand the heat from voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for the newspapers to beat him on everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
He was a bit of a bully, I'm sure.
But he didn't silence his critics.
For in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech may be taken away - and, dumb and silent, we are led like sheep to the slaughter".
Which brings me to Maryland, where Governor Larry Hogan has to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's staff have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online commentary was full of a counter-reaction with "So what?"
"It's just Facebook", said a lot of people.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in a vastly democratic state who is incredibly popular.
He has the second highest approval of the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in the running of his state and a strict adherence to principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as his primary means to connect with his constituents, and playfully debuting his hairless post-chemotherapy head on his site.
So blocking people from coming to the governor's site - which is a public forum that is called official and staffed with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that the comment blocking was nothing more than a moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people waving whip online.
The Post talked to some of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, a businessman and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not profane.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, MD, was not hate-filled, but she did ask about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other breaking news", she wrote in the comment section of The Post news show.
"I don't like the idea either, that if a number of people take a stand on the same issue, then they are disregarded by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of concerned citizens".
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack" would probably be called "speech".
The Facebook era makes it easy to cut a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than in earlier times, when the same thing would have been done, that staff were sent to collect and burn critical editorials or arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for using Facebook and other social media to insult.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who were blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones in this regard was reached last week in Virginia.
The chair of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's day, the era of the affordable port had an effect similar to the Internet.
Newspaper circulation multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers responded to his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people using the pseudonyms "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, trade and shipping with Britain, overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he didn't shut her up.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
