Less lung cancer caused by secondhand smoke
Over the past two decades, fewer people have died from lung cancer as a result of secondhand smoke.
This is the conclusion reached by scientists at the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) in a study.
"We estimate that passive smoking causes 167 lung cancer deaths a year", said Heiko Becher, who led the study.
As a comparison, he drew on his own study on the subject from 1994.
At that time, there were still 400 lung cancer deaths per year in Germany due to secondhand smoke.
The new study was published in the International Journal of Public Health.
