Poverty and Death in the Indonesian Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
She rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regency in the restive Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato - locally called "nota" - directly into the chimney.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed with eager, unwashed hands and swallowed.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most of the villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are the soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m"., she says.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote by a public hand-picking in front of the occupying forces.
An existing pro-independence movement against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which controls the region and excludes foreign journalists or observers from it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate, and the journey involves a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire, and then a morning five-hour drive by rental car.
There is no public transportation.
The city of some 19,000 people is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated tin roofs that have been transformed by rust into various shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made their way here, let alone journalists and practically no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, the Papuans of Mee Pago worshiped a god called Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to her vibrant handwoven turban, dark shirt, and light-colored skirt.
"We used to have leaves on our bodies".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28 percent of the population lives below the poverty line and has some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a stifling presence.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden geese and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970s were considered genocide by the Asian Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We will lose everything", said a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities in the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electric shocks are particularly popular according to another report - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week", said Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The population of 3.5 million in the province is 83% Christian, but the demographic trend is changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese Warung canteens sell fried chicken and Gado-Gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting to keep up.
"Migrants have started selling chickens and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the local Papuans", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, to work.
"It has cost the native Papuans - the Mama-Mama [women] of Papua - their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address inequalities and violations in Papua.
The former carpenter secured 27 of the 29 districts of Papua - including Paniai - on his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, expecting that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored", You says.
In fact, Paniai suffered a low point just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols around a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke through the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offence at her tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers, who had been drinking, chased and beat the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government commission building was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papua men, women and children gathered at a football field outside the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - walking in circles and imitating a bird's song - of the Papuas Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military posts.
When the mood was heating up, an internal radio command was sent to the soldiers: "If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them dead", states an official document of TIME, which was not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood of Enarotali, saw the imminent danger and called for calm and asked the crowd to return home.
Nobody was in the mood to listen.
"As I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist", he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired", he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shootings.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Yohanes, who like many Indonesians has only one name, told TIME in a somber mood.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him".
Chief Inspector of the Papua Police, Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only "securing" their station because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", said Papua Police spokesman, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings was not filtered to Jakarta until the next day.
For three weeks, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the historical wrongs in Papua.
"I want this case to be resolved immediately so that it won't happen again in the future", he said.
