The point is that we have committed to address these violations, but there are processes that need to be gone through", he said.
Then Wiranto made a retreat when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on June 5 and said he had no plans to establish a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, "everything is regulated by law", he said.
Wiranto, who has been charged by the UN with "crimes against humanity" that led to more than 1,000 deaths in East Timor's bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
Families of the Paniai victims greeted such claims with bitter disbelief.
"I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there has been no progress", says Yohanes.
"I'm tired of it".
He says that years later, he's still living in fear.
"I'm scared", he says.
