In 1267, the St. Hilariuskapelle was first mentioned in the Württembergese record book: Count Hermann von Sulz sold "the mountain with the parish church to Tumlingen including the Vogtei" to Magister Eberhard von Horb and his brother Dietrich for 20 Mark Silber.
According to the text of the document, on the Tumlinger Berg, in addition to the former parish church, there was also a court of the lord to which the church or the patronage belonged and not vice versa.
So there were people living there, too.
As the description of the Oberamt Freudenstadt from 1858 shows, the third "berg" was the village's main settlement, along with the sub-village and the upper village, which can still be seen in the village of Tumlingen today.
Old maps from about the year 1600 support these historical facts.
The right of patronage arose from the early medieval right of the Church.
A lord who built, equipped and staffed a church with a pastor remained the owner of that church and could inherit that church as well.
This included the right to appoint a pastor or to suggest a new one to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
The larger of the two was destroyed on Christmas Day 1673.
The new bell was first rung in 1692, but later had to be surrendered in 1942 during World War II.
During the Thirty Years' War (1616-1648) the windows were smashed and the bell-shapes were stolen.
The roof was leaking.
In 1796, French troops camped near the church.
They took out the pulpit and the chairs and used them as firewood.
The remains of the church threatened to collapse in 1809.
Until 1869, the Tumlinger Hilarius cemetery also served as the final resting place for the dead from Hörschweiler.
In 1823 the cemetery was enlarged and the Hilariuskirche was demolished.
Only the church tower was left standing.
On New Year's Eve, 1834, a storm split the church tower in two and half of it collapsed.
To prevent a misfortune, the tower was demolished.
Only the tower dwarf survived to this day as a witness to the 750-year-old church history.
Today, Horst Kallenberger and Rolf-Dieter Wasem of the "Selfish Retirees" as successors of Dieter Dockhorn maintain the Hilarius plant.
