A 1948 Ford Mercury drove through a crowd of spectators in rural Monroe, Georgia, and rammed its way onto the Ford Bridge at Moore.
Before the car, with four black passengers and a white driver, could reach the bridge, a group of white men with rifles emerged to block its path.
The leader of the mob - a middle-aged man in a pinstripe suit - took a long puff of his cigar and peered through the windshield.
Inside, the inmates were terrified.
"We want this n--r Roger!" roared the man.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams ripped through the silence as a young black man was dragged from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene played on July 22 is only a reenactment.
But then when a noose was thrown around "Roger"'s neck, almost everyone in the audience let out a very real sigh.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to recreate the night that two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey - were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
No one was ever charged for the murders.
"It's really unbelievable that in all these years not a single person has been arrested - even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are", said Tyrone Brooks, who is helping to organize the retreat.
"It's a stain on a story, but it's a burden on our souls".
Brooks is a 71-year-old former congressman from the state of Georgia and a lifelong civil rights activist.
For him, the reenactment serves as a dramatic call to action and is an annual reminder to the Monroe community that an injustice was never corrected.
"We want prosecution, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we must get justice", he said.
"We cannot achieve healing and reconciliation until we have justice".
A forensic pathologist lays a bed sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Moore-Ford lynch on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties have been suspected in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been on the loose for decades, civil rights activists say the double motivation for the lynchings has always been known throughout the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in the summer primary.
At about the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black farmer Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight - allegedly over a woman.
Brooks said the word in town was that Hester had slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the baby she was carrying wasn't from her husband.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to free Malcolm from prison, according to the FBI.
He was accompanied to the prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But then as they were moving away from the prison and approaching Moore's Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison was the one who planned and ordered the murders", concludes an FBI report.
"It is also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement, "who not only participated in the killings, but also suppressed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
