Her portrayal is vivid, poignant, and rooted in a kind of deep racism that many would like to believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to look at, and even harder to look away, but Greene said that's the point.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because we'll be confronted with the ugliness of it in all of us", she said.
"But I can't have a relationship with you if you don't want to listen to me or hear what I've been through".
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white and the rest black - huddled in a room and listened as Greene began a well-rehearsed overview of the play.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's co-director here.
He's been playing the role of chief clan member for years, but he said the role never gets easier.
"I feel dirty because I'm not like that", Marbaugh said.
"But I think it's very important to keep this story alive, because we don't want to go back to those times".
Across the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, were rehearsing their lines.
The play begins with Malcolm, the horse, screaming and harassing him, angry that he slept with his wife Dorothy.
"I said, n--he, get off my property!"
Rascona is returning fire.
There's a break.
And then everybody (at least all the black actors) burst out laughing.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What?" asked Rascona.
He's alarmed and confused.
Was I too harsh?
"No", said Greene, still giggling.
"I just don't think white people said 'he' back then".
"But", one of the other black actors quipped.
"You just have to hit the hard 'R.'".
And that's when the energy shifts in the room, and a sense of camaraderie replaces the uneasiness.
Everyone is busy getting this right, not just for the game, but for the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene begins again.
