New results of Swedish asylum age assessment tests published
The latest results of tests on asylum seekers in Sweden who underwent a new method of medical assessment of their age show that more than 80 percent of those tested are over the age of 18, but not everyone believes the results are accurate.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started carrying out the tests last year.
They are intended to improve the accuracy of age assessment during the asylum procedure after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "likely to be under 18 years of age".
The tests are only done in cases where the age of the person is in question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent for the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics from the past months, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 years of age does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his or her age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases that "suggest the person being tested was 18 years or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would turn 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves taking X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
One skeptic is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of people to see whether they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think that's the kind of measurement that should be used.
It's very uncertain to judge biological age in this way.
If we cannot say for sure, we should not pretend we can", he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is small.
The greatest risk is when the person is just under 18, in which case it is about 10 per cent".
