Nostalgia is going to the nitty-gritty in "Wet Hot American Summer" and "Comrade Detective".
This re-telling of the story is both nostalgic for the characters' glory days in the 1980s, for the 1990s grunge era (when pioneers David Wain and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy "The State" for MTV), and for themselves - that is, for 2001, before its stars, such as Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd, went on to bigger things.
As a cultural artifact, it is both a parody and an embodiment of our Facebook-enabled era of permanent memories.
But as a franchise, it feels like time is running out.
"First Day of Camp" did surprisingly well, not only because of its absurd humor (it included an original story for a talking can of vegetables, spoken by H. Jon Benjamin).
By sticking to the core of the gag - middle-aged actors playing horny kids growing up - they still managed to make it impossible to recapture the last bit of the joke.
"Ten Years Later", with its adults now playing adults, is less emotionally rooted and its parody is more of a watering can, including a riff on the 1990s stalker films such as "The Hand That Rocks the Cradle".
At one point, a character stumbles through an Apple Powerbook, some inline skates, and "a bunch of other things from 1991".
Many of the central stories are the same.
The lovable Coop (Mr. Showalter), now a novelist, has not yet forgotten Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) has not lost his virginity.
And there is another crazy evil plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Mr. Showalter) who is now being supported by George H. W. Bush (a well-crafted impression of Michael Ian Black).
As always, the field trips are the best part of the franchise.
It's especially fun to see the ever-young Mr. Rudd showing off Matt Dillon's under-lip from "Singles", whose former big-man-on-camp Andy now feels like an old fart.
It's the moments of random madness that could fuel this franchise like a sort of recurring "Seven Up!" series until it reaches what I think is its logical conclusion: "Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later", whose final scene will show the gang attending the film premiere of "Wet Hot American Summer".
"Comrade Detective" on Amazon is now a reminder of a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War revival of "The Americans", the movie "Atomic Blonde", and even "GLOW" with its East versus West ringing iconography.
The comedy created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Rhys Thomas claims to be a found TV series: a Romanian drama of the eighties with the two policemen as friends, two officers from Bucharest who fight for truth, atheism and the path of Marxism-Leninism.
The main roles - a tough-minded Gregor and an idealistic Iosef - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Corneliu Ulici, whose dialogues are dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a great idea.
But it's not much more than an idea.
There are some nice gags to watch (the police spend their time watching chess on TV, like Americans might do with football).
And the list of famous speakers - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny - makes for a decent game of 'Find the Voice'.
But "Comrade Detective" is so committed to the truthfulness of a desperate propaganda drama - a murderer wearing a Reagan mask is involved - that it often plays as one.
Six long episodes, it's dragging on, and the comedy isn't fast enough or frequent enough.
"Comrade Detective", edited to a shorter length, could better deliver his agitatory satire, as Gregor and Iosef keep visiting the American Embassy, whose lobby is always occupied by two fat men who devour a bunch of hamburgers.
The message for the imaginary communist audience is that Western culture can make anything into food for a guelage.
The fictional Romanian creators were not wrong: we are even doing it with our own younger history and with theirs.
