NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be given access to 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment in the NHS from September, following a fight in the High Court against funding the drug.
NHS England has announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent, is now being delivered by the NHS in an initial three-year study involving an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal last year upheld a High Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was hailed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as "an important new intervention", while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called it a "defining moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to sign up, with more clinics to follow in October before it is rolled out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a series of HIV medicines taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there is just enough medicine in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day for up to two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify suitable participants to consent to the study, including men, women, transgender persons and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People living in England and registered with a GP can also register for possible participation at their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is being used, taken up and implemented in a targeted way on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention was intended to complement and overtake the widespread and increasingly successful HIV prevention efforts.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity's greatest health challenges".
Deborah Gold, chief executive of the National Aids Trust, said: "This is a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if it is targeted to people who are vulnerable and in need, has the potential to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which leads to the improvement of many, many lives.
We welcome this announcement".
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now is to get the trial across the country quickly and to ensure that no one is left behind who is at risk of HIV.
Now that PrEP is available, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people who are infected with HIV".
Sharon Hodgson, the shadow health minister, said: "The start of the PrEP trial is welcome and overdue after months of delay and hesitant government implementation.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and ending the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This trial brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
