The staff of the weekly Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to review their plans for covering the recent chaos in Sinaloa State caused by organized crime, corrupt officials and the ongoing drug wars.
But on this day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to talk about safety.
They were told that it was important to change their routines.
Two senior journalists are discussing which feels safer: to take their children, who were the target of a grenade attack in 2009, to the office or to leave them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a board on the front of the room: Enemies, Neutrals, Allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column - no proof is needed, perceptions and gut feelings are enough.
There are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being on the payroll of the government or the cartels, a catalog of criminals who make the chaos of Mexico dangerous.
There is no end to the violence, and while the country is piling up bodies, more and more journalists are joining in: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats, and so far this year there have been at least seven deaths in seven states.
Among the latter is its editor and inspirer of Riodoce, the co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist", wrote Valdez in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His absence is deeply felt, though his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdez showing his middle finger with the word "Justice" hanging on the Riodoce building's facade, two reporters in their thirties, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wearing T-shirts showing his smiling face with glasses or his typical Panamahut.
The workshop takes place less than two months after his death, and the reporters discuss their shared themes, the trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecution was established in 2010 to handle cases of journalists, it has only initiated two criminal proceedings, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders each year linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
At Riodoce, they still insist on dealing with the violence of Sinaloa, even though they are inconsolable and even though the terrain is now more treacherous.
Without information about the killers, without justice, the meeting to discuss security is of little use, Ibarra says.
"It's very stupid to waste my time in this workshop", he says.
"Until we know why, we distrust everyone".
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the office of the newspaper Riodoce in the state capital of Culiacan.
He managed to drive a few blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men, forced out of his car and shot at him 12 times, presumably because of the name of the newspaper - which translates to "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove away in his car and damaged it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumors tend to fly free in Culiacan.
But there is virtually nothing but silence on the subject of Valdez.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlefields, as rival factions fight to fill the vacuum.
It doesn't matter that in Sinaloa, every day, someone or several people are shot in the street, or that the cemetery is full of decorated, two-story mausoleums for drug lords, larger than many houses for the living.
Forget for a minute that there is a state of "tranquility" when only one cartel has control of the coastal state with its valuable ports and drug trafficking routes into the United States.
Despite this, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, a co-founder and director of Riodoce, is wracked with guilt over not being able to protect his friend.
He believes that two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First, in February, an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival cartel factions at war with Guzman's sons, was published.
This publication may have angered the Sons, as suspected gang members bought up every copy of the issue as it was delivered to newsstands.
The second mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is considered a milestone in Mexican violence against journalists.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be there.
He was a veteran reporter for Northwest in 2003 when he joined forces with five colleagues to found Riodoce and sold $50 of his stake.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without coming across the drug problem", Bojorquez said.
In time, the newspaper gained a reputation for courageous and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved to publish hard-hitting investigative stories without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by a publication where they could read stories no one else dared cover.
Eight years after the founding of Riodoce, she received the prestigious "Maria-Moors-Cabot Prize" for her reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in pursuing Mexico's drug history wherever it led.
He freely admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to live", he said at the time of the CPJ award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa "is a way of life", he said in an interview with Rompeviento-TV last October.
"You have to do the job that comes with being a journalist - either that or play dumb.
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do in the face of so many dead people... why didn't you tell us what was going on?"
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the fun-loving bird who could curse like a dockworker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and sit at the same table there.
Now they ask, was his love of routine his undoing?
His death has also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their job and stay alive.
"They don't like you to deal with their wives, their children, their clean businesses, their secret runways" to move drugs.
"These things were not allowed", Bojorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, is a high degree of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trust your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble is, said the editor of Riodoce Andres Villarreal, that "smell is a sense that can be deceived ... and then the thing with Javier happens".
The old rules, as he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - just as they don't in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
The room where Riodoce employees were meeting for security training suddenly had no cell phones, and days earlier it was revealed that spyware sold exclusively to governments was being used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two policemen were seeking shelter from the 104 degrees (40 C) heat in the shade of a tree.
They were assigned by the state government to protect the offices of Riodoce in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood of Culiacan.
Partly in jest, some of the reporters wondered if these officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself described as untrustworthy.
It's been months since the reporters went to the mountainous country where the drug gangs are de facto under control.
For this week's issue, Riodoce has looked at three main stories.
There was the murder of the brother of the former famous boxer Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
They also had an exhibition on state expenditures, focused on the governor's hometown.
And there was a group that carried out a kidnapping in one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block away from the prosecutor's office.
There was no official word on who was kidnapped or how it happened, so caution was required when it came time to write what everyone in town knows: that the restaurant is a favorite haunt of drug dealers and law enforcement.
A reporter learned from public records that the restaurant was registered under the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolution Party (PRI), which dominated all political levels for almost a century.
Recently, several PRI governors were accused of high-profile corruption.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents in this restaurant, including one in which a son of "El Chapo" Guzman escaped a military raid.
Just a few months earlier, readers would have considered Valdez's column the best-informed source on the abduction.
"We would have known what happened before", said Villarreal, 46, who is nicknamed "El Flaco" because of his slender build.
"Now all channels of communication with our sources are broken".
The Valdez office has become a repository for signs and stickers protesting the murder of journalists, rededicated because the staff have become something they never expected to be: activists in the name of the press.
