According to reports in National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk while digging in the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
He came upon something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500-pound (1,100-kg) lump of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished product is now ready to be unveiled.
"If you blink your eyes just a little bit, you could almost believe it was asleep", said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
"It will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs".
Researchers have found that this herbivore, although covered in armor and resembling a walking tank, was likely threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a shielding technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend better with its environment and evade its enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million year old creature from the Nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Now researchers have studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor over its body.
They discovered counter-shading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although counter-shading is common, the results are surprising, since boreal opelta far exceed the size of animals living today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was being chased by enough pressure from flesh-eating dinosaurs, that evolution favored the concealment of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most of the contemporary animals that use counter shading -- think of deer, zebras, or armadillos -- are much smaller and more vulnerable to predation, which signals that this Nodosaurus was in a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous must have been", said Brown.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists are continuing to study the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was carried out to the sea, where it sank backwards to the bottom of the sea.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida today, and rivers and oceans were likely much farther inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, but it is also preserved in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal", said Brown.
"The result is that the animal looks almost exactly as it did in the early Cretaceous.
