She stumbled across a post from someone from high school.
"The police just killed an 18-year-old child, and he is still lying in the street", it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was live tweeting the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying in the street and would stay there for four hours.
"This is wild", Ferrell thought.
But death was not new to them and their community.
She hung up her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later in the evening.
There were pictures of the police band and people screaming, and a man claiming to be Brown's father wearing a sign that said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another officer unlocked his rifle and shouted, "I'm going to kill you... all animals".
"That's not common", Ferrell recalled her statement.
"This is not the kind of murder we're used to seeing and can call typical".
At that moment, I felt a shiver.
I was angry and I cried".
She booked a flight back and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two of them would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?
It's a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, told from the perspective of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who wore a flower dress and a matching crown, the two men discussed a conversation they had had countless times before that morning about the black experience and the black condition.
"Remember how I taught you that black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take her", Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is the culmination of what happened in the past.
She has to know it and see it and be brought up in it.
It has to be well developed, not just activism and organization, but also knowing the different layers of black experience and black constitution and what we have to do to be free, to free ourselves.
Even if I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't experience blatant racism in person, she's no different than the next black female child.
I feel that I would be doing her a disservice by keeping her away from it".
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place across from the police station that became a campsite as the activists waited for the possible non-prosecution of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped to distribute them to protesters.
A new kind of activism was slowly taking shape for Ferrell.
"My activism has changed completely after 9/11, " she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association, focusing on food equity and health disparities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come".
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Farrar, were just trying to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document it or are you trying to find a story that you can exploit?"
And this skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often white people, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson didn't center their voices, and we wanted to do it differently".
Folayan had already worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist from the area known for his activism around death row inmates.
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project, and he, along with six other locals, followed the Whose Streets? team in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone speaking for us or speaking to us. We are speaking", Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed".
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement is "not about a messiah-leader, but about a community coming together", Folayan said - she proved to be the film's most outspoken participant.
As a result, documents from Whose Streets? reveal surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, as she falls in love and marries his wife.
"I felt like I was naked", said Ferrell, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I've come to understand that in this work and in humanizing black people, there has to be a certain vulnerability".
In addition, Ferrell's story echoes the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who made the film "BlacklivesMatter" a social media phenomenon after the killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement overall", Ferrell said, "and so we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to carry the brunt of it all".
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being sustained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action", in which Ferrell was chosen because of her identity as the heart of the film.
"She was the person who stirred up this energy", she said.
"It's no coincidence that she was on the front lines, "because there's so much at stake in a life at these crossroads as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen".
Now, the news cameras in Ferguson are long gone, but the racial ties between the community and the police are still there.
Ferrell is on probation for two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls home: "A chaos".
But she clings to a song and she feels committed to this memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains".
