A fitting resemblance: artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York, you can see many faces -- white, black and brown, almost imperceptibly alike -- hanging from cables from the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek swabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clips from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence after leaking classified diplomatic cables through the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transwoman and seminal dissident whose conviction was overturned by Barack Obama when he was just three days into office.
Dewey-Hagborg, by algorithmically analyzing the DNA that was extracted by Manning and created from the 30 portraits of what someone with this genomic data might look like, has created a sharp, if somewhat intellectual commentary not only on the malleability of DNA data -- the many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations -- but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since her adolescence, was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
The prison had suppressed her image so much that there was only one photo - a grainy, black-and-white selfie, in which Manning was visibly uncomfortable sitting in a driver's seat wearing a platinum blonde wig - that she was associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was coming off the heels of the great success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts like cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting the DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That's when she got an email from a newspaper magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning while she was in prison and they wanted a kind of portrait to accompany this article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't be visited at that time, and she couldn't be photographed, so you contacted Chelsea and asked her to do a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequal pen pals, exchanging several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic book, "Suppressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, that foresaw a future in which President Chelsea would reverse her judgment and be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually, just days after the book was published, call for Manning's release after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas was a welcome sort of happy reunion.
There's something deep and strong about the opening of the exhibition, as Donald Trump wages a war against government informants and transgender troops to find new, two-pronged ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to be fixing.
When Dewey-Hagborg was asked about the strange timing of all of this, she said, "Things happen for a reason".
In an artistic statement written on the wall of the gallery, Manning, with her oversized signature below it (the "i" in her family name is marked with a heart), called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite wall is her mitochondrial DNA sequence -- a thousandth of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
Dewey-Hagborg hoped that by including the 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific lexicon) she would show how amazingly similar, at least in biological terms, we all are.
"What I hope people take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open to interpretation genetic data is and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work Spurious Memories is also on display.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so this is 30 of those stories".
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in a separate room, is a page from the aforementioned comic novel.
It shows Manning emerging from the United States' disciplinary prisons like King Kong with a public address system in her hand.
"If they can put you down, they've won", they say.
"So never shut your mouth".
"It came straight from a letter she wrote to me", said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
"It still gives me goose bumps to talk about it".
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person - as anticipated in the comic book - but if she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, her own genomic simulacra, who will converge like hordes of protesters.
This was also targeted, like everything in the exhibition, down to the size (5' 2", Manning's height), where their genetic haplogroups were written in pencil.
"In the past, I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that was formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was also behind her liberation".
