Creating a comic novel: a castle in the history of England
In its recent past, the small Scotney Castle has featured in a squeeze music video and was a safe haven for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has lived through 700 years of turbulent history from its cosy seat in the Bewl River Valley in Kent and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-headed Yorkshireman with a penchant for historical documents.
"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years", he says sorrowfully.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand".
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era, documenting the families who lived in Scotney, each story illustrated by a different up-and-coming British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It's not the first book by Rhodes to be based on an archive: he wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I only reacted to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins", he says.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days, people would light a fire to get the light.
To someone 300 years later, the smell has the effect of being present.
I love the archives!"
For someone so wrapped up in old papers, being supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and living in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I overestimated my welcome a bit"), all this seems too good to be true.
Rhodos spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing the archives, and studying the castle's many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyenas' heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the trench.
He wandered through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and talked with landscapers, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he drank whiskey and started writing.
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access in 2006 when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff had just begun to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years where aristocrats said, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You'd think land conflicts would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a birch that two families were fighting over.
Boys, let it all out!"
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into English history on a broader basis, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot which occurred in the castle in 1380, in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex'", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in this area and I thought a revolt was a good start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle's history - such as 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery that was only made years later when his coffin was excavated).
The DarreIIs are Rhodes's favourite family from Scotney: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, always going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking boys with a talent for recruiting heiresses".
After his time at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a comic book about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave again", he says.
It was like, "Oh, now I have to deal with my fucking life again".
