Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may help to reduce IBD
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could alleviate the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, which affects some 1.3 million in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While those affected are typically advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to ensure that harmful microbes lurking in food do not enter the body.
Cells that are capable of causing inflammation are counterbalanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too far in the direction of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can result.
In experiments, it was found that a type of tolerance-promoting immune cell is found in mice that carry a certain bacterium in their intestines.
And the bacterium needs tryptophan -- one of the building blocks of protein -- to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a bacterial species - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet promotes a more tolerant, less inflammatory intestinal environment if the same system works in humans.
Postdoctoral student Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan was investigating a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain, but housed separately, did not.
She suspected that the difference was related to the mice's gut microbiomes - the community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice's intestines were sequenced for DNA, and they found six types of bacteria that were present in the mice with the immune cells, but were missing in the mice without them.
So, mice were raised in a sterile environment, so they lacked an intestinal microbiome and they didn't develop that type of immune cell, and they got L. reuteri and the immune cells were formed.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active ingredient was cleared from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tracts.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri develop in human cells as they do in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said: "The development of these cells is probably something we want to encourage, since these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially, high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri may lead to an expansion of this population.'
