Afghan democracy depends on women's political role, says UN
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the UN mission, said hundreds of women will be running in the provincial council elections, three women are running for the vice-presidential role and more than 30 percent of the newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated", he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are included in all parts of the electoral process.
Afghan provincial council and presidential elections will be held on April 5.
The Taliban have issued threats against an electoral process, which coincides with the transition of international combat operations to a consultative role.
This year's elections will mark the first peaceful transfer of power from one democratically elected government to the next.
Haysom said a strong role for women will further strengthen Afghanistan's democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Election Commission reports that 1.2 million women are registered to vote out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters.
