GMB's concern about investment in the McVitie plant in Glasgow
A union wants to ask managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie about the long-term commitment to production at their Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company had been silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea Biscuits.
McVitie's owner Pladis said he's invested more than £5 million in the past few years.
He added that employees and union representatives would be "the first to know" if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland asked McVitie's to "express its concern that the financing for the modernisation of production lines is not being advanced".
GMB senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we cannot get clarity from the General Site Manager on Tollcross's business needs and investment plans for the future is deeply concerning for our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily focused on the local community and the Greater Glasgow area, an important pillar of decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, in the context of jobs, wages and prosperity, and in the context of Brexit, rising costs of living and chronic production decline, the east end of Glasgow is in dire need of a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie.'
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: 'The branch manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday and the company will respond directly as we appreciate the continued commitment of staff and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some issues were discussed openly.
We discussed with the staff that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our businesses and locations - to remain competitive.
She added: 'In recent years we have invested over £5 million in our toll-cross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a manufacturing site and should our operations change at the site, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know".
